52 // ######################################################################
53 // Partitioner tunable settings:
54 //
55 // Before describing these settings, a bit of background:
56 //
57 // Early during the development of the partitioner, V3Split was failing to
58 // split large always blocks (with ~100K assignments) so we had to handle
59 // very large vertices with ~100K incoming and outgoing edges.
60 //
61 // The partitioner attempts to deal with such densely connected
62 // graphs. Some of the tuning parameters below reference "huge vertices",
63 // that's what they're talking about, vertices with tens of thousands of
64 // edges in and out. Whereas most graphs have only tens of edges in and out
65 // of most vertices.
66 //
67 // V3Split has since been fixed to more reliably split large always
68 // blocks. It's kind of an open question whether the partitioner must
69 // handle huge nodes gracefully. Maybe not! But it still can, given
70 // appropriate tuning.
71
72 // PART_SIBLING_EDGE_LIMIT (integer)
73 //
74 // Arbitrarily limit the number of edges on a single vertex that will be
75 // considered when enumerating siblings, to the given value. This protects
76 // the partitioner runtime in the presence of huge vertices.
77 //
78 // The sibling-merge is less important than the edge merge. (You can
79 // totally disable the sibling merge and get halfway decent partitions; you
80 // can't disable edge merges, those are fundamental to the process.) So,
81 // skipping the enumeration of some siblings on a few vertices does not
82 // have a large impact on the result of the partitioner.
83 //
84 // If your vertices are small, the limit (at 26) approaches a no-op. Hence
85 // there's basically no cost to applying this limit even when we don't
86 // expect huge vertices.
87 //
88 // If you don't care about partitioner runtime and you want the most
89 // aggressive partition, set the limit very high. If you have huge
90 // vertices, leave this as is.
91 constexpr unsigned PART_SIBLING_EDGE_LIMIT = 26;
92
93 // PART_STEPPED_COST (defined/undef)
94 //
95 // When computing critical path costs, use a step function on the actual
96 // underlying vertex cost.
97 //
98 // If there are huge vertices, when a tiny vertex merges into a huge
99 // vertex, we can often avoid increasing the huge vertex's stepped cost.
100 // If the stepped cost hasn't increased, and the critical path into the huge
101 // vertex hasn't increased, we can avoid propagating a new critical path to
102 // vertices past the huge vertex. Since huge vertices tend to have huge lists
103 // of children and parents, this can be a substantial savings.
104 //
105 // Does not seem to reduce the quality of the partitioner's output.
106 //
107 // If you have huge vertices, leave this 'true', it is the major setting
108 // that allows the partitioner to handle such difficult graphs on anything
109 // like a human time scale.
110 //
111 // If you don't have huge vertices, the 'true' value doesn't help much but
112 // should cost almost nothing in terms of partitioner quality.
113 //
114 // If you want the most aggressive possible partition, set it "false" and
115 // be prepared to be disappointed when the improvement in the partition is
116 // negligible / in the noise.
117 //
118 // Q) Why retain the control, if there is really no downside?
119 //
120 // A) Cost stepping can lead to corner cases. A developer may wish to
121 // disable cost stepping to rule it out as the cause of unexpected
122 // behavior.
123 #define PART_STEPPED_COST true
124
125 // Don't produce more than a certain maximum number of MTasks. This helps
126 // the TSP variable sort not to blow up (a concern for some of the tests)
127 // and we probably don't want a huge number of mTaskGraphp in practice anyway
128 // (50 to 100 is typical.)
129 //
130 // If the user doesn't give one with '--threads-max-mTaskGraphp', we'll set the
131 // maximum # of MTasks to
132 // (# of threads * PART_DEFAULT_MAX_MTASKS_PER_THREAD)
133 constexpr unsigned PART_DEFAULT_MAX_MTASKS_PER_THREAD = 50;
134
135 // end tunables.

781 // Propagate increasing critical path (CP) costs through a graph.

803 UDEBUGONLY(UASSERT(score >= m_score, "Must increase"););
804 ✗ m_score = score;

807 ✗ if (m_score != other.m_score) return m_score < other.m_score;
808 ✗ return LogicMTask::CmpLogicMTask{}(m_mtaskp, other.m_mtaskp);

901 ✗ void go() {
902 constexpr GraphWay way{N_Way};
903 constexpr GraphWay inv{way.invert()};
904
905 // m_pending maps each pending vertex to the amount that it wayward
906 // CP will grow.
907 //
908 // We can iterate over the pending set in reverse order, always
909 // choosing the nodes with the largest pending CP-growth.
910 //
911 // The intuition is: if the original seed node had its CP grow by
912 // 50, the most any wayward node can possibly grow is also 50. So
913 // for anything pending to grow by 50, we know we can process it
914 // once and we won't have to grow its CP again on the current pass.
915 // After we're done with all the grow-by-50s, nothing else will
916 // grow by 50 again on the current pass, and we can process the
917 // grow-by-49s and we know we'll only have to process each one
918 // once. And so on.
919 //
920 // This generalizes to multiple seed nodes also.
921 ✗ while (!m_pendingHeap.empty()) {
922 // Pop max element from heap
923 ✗ PendingHeapNode* const maxp = m_pendingHeap.max();
924 ✗ m_pendingHeap.remove(maxp);
925 // Pick up values
926 ✗ LogicMTask* const mtaskp = maxp->key().m_mtaskp;
927 ✗ const uint32_t cpGrowBy = maxp->key().m_score;
928 // Free the heap node, we are done with it
929 freeNode(maxp);
930 mtaskp->userp(nullptr);
931 // Update the critPathCost of mtaskp, that was out-of-date with respect to its edges
932 const uint32_t startCp = mtaskp->critPathCost(way);
933 ✗ const uint32_t newCp = startCp + cpGrowBy;
934 ✗ if (VL_UNLIKELY(m_slowAsserts)) {
935 // Check that CP matches that of the longest edge wayward of vxp.
936 ✗ const uint32_t edgeCp = mtaskp->m_edgeHeap[inv].max()->key().m_score;
937 ✗ UASSERT_OBJ(edgeCp == newCp, mtaskp, "CP doesn't match longest wayward edge");

939 // important property of PropagateCp which allows it to be far
940 // faster than a recursive algorithm on some graphs.
941 const bool first = m_seen.insert(mtaskp).second;
942 ✗ UASSERT_OBJ(first, mtaskp, "Set CP on node twice");
943 }
944 mtaskp->setCritPathCost(way, newCp);
945 ✗ cpHasIncreased(mtaskp, newCp + mtaskp->stepCost());
946 }

948 ✗ if (VL_UNLIKELY(m_slowAsserts)) m_seen.clear();

1001 // Merge edges from a LogicMtask.
1002 ✗ static void partRedirectEdgesFrom(V3Graph& graph, LogicMTask* recipientp, LogicMTask* donorp,
1003 MergeCandidateScoreboard* sbp) {
1004 // This code removes adjacent edges. When this occurs, mark it in need
1005 // of a rescore, in case its score has fallen and we need to move it up
1006 // toward the front of the scoreboard.
1007 //
1008 // Wait, what? Shouldn't the scores only increase as we merge nodes? Well
1009 // that's almost true. But there is one exception.
1010 //
1011 // Suppose we have A->B, B->C, and A->C.
1012 //
1013 // The A->C edge is a "transitive" edge. It's ineligible to be merged, as
1014 // the merge would create a cycle. We score it on the scoreboard like any
1015 // other edge.
1016 //
1017 // However, our "score" estimate for A->C is bogus, because the forward
1018 // critical path to C and the reverse critical path to A both contain the
1019 // same node (B) so we overestimate the score of A->C. At first this
1020 // doesn't matter, since transitive edges aren't eligible to merge anyway.
1021 //
1022 // Later, suppose the edge contractor decides to merge the B->C edge, with
1023 // B donating all its incoming edges into C, say. (So we reach this
1024 // function.)
1025 //
1026 // With B going away, the A->C edge will no longer be transitive and it
1027 // will become eligible to merge. But if we don't mark it for rescore,
1028 // it'll stay in the scoreboard with its old (overestimate) score. We'll
1029 // merge it too late due to the bogus score. When we finally merge it, we
1030 // fail the assert in the main edge contraction loop which checks that the
1031 // actual score did not fall below the scoreboard's score.
1032 //
1033 // Another way of stating this: this code ensures that scores of
1034 // non-transitive edges only ever increase.
1035
1036 // Process outgoing edges
1037 ✗ while (MTaskEdge* const edgep = static_cast<MTaskEdge*>(donorp->outEdges().frontp())) {

1048 ✗ recipientp->findConnectingEdgep<GraphWay::FORWARD>(relativep));

1051 }
1052 ✗ VL_DO_DANGLING(edgep->unlinkDelete(), edgep);
1053 } else {

1055 // Redirect the edge from donor<->relative to recipient<->relative.
1056 ✗ edgep->relinkFromp(recipientp);
1057 ✗ recipientp->addRelativeMTask(relativep);
1058 recipientp->stealRelativeEdge<GraphWay::FORWARD>(edgep);
1059 ✗ relativep->addRelativeEdge<GraphWay::REVERSE>(edgep);
1060 ✗ if (sbp) {

1063 } else {

1740 //######################################################################
1741 // FixDataHazards
1742
1743 class FixDataHazards final {
1744 //
1745 // Fix data hazards in the MTask graph.
1746 //
1747 // The fine-grained graph from V3Order may contain data hazards which are
1748 // not a problem for serial mode, but which would be a problem in parallel
1749 // mode.
1750 //
1751 // There are basically two classes: unordered pairs of writes, and
1752 // unordered write-read pairs. We fix both here, with a combination of
1753 // MTask-merges and new edges to ensure no such unordered pairs remain.
1754 //
1755 // ABOUT UNORDERED WRITE-WRITE PAIRS
1756 //
1757 // The V3Order dependency graph treats these as unordered events:
1758 //
1759 // a) sig[15:8] = stuff;
1760 // ...
1761 // b) sig[7:0] = other_stuff;
1762 //
1763 // Seems OK right? They are writes to disjoint bits of the same
1764 // signal. They can run in either order, in serial mode, and the result
1765 // will be the same.
1766 //
1767 // The resulting C code for each of this isn't a pure write, it's
1768 // actually an R-M-W sequence:
1769 //
1770 // a) sig = (sig & 0xff) | (0xff00 & (stuff << 8));
1771 // ...
1772 // b) sig = (sig & 0xff00) | (0xff & other_stuff);
1773 //
1774 // In serial mode, order doesn't matter so long as these run serially.
1775 // In parallel mode, we must serialize these RMW's to avoid a race.
1776 //
1777 // We don't actually check here if each write would involve an R-M-W, we
1778 // just assume that it would. If this routine ever causes a drastic
1779 // increase in critical path, it could be optimized to make a better
1780 // prediction (with all the risk that word implies!) about whether a
1781 // given write is likely to turn into an R-M-W.
1782 //
1783 // ABOUT UNORDERED WRITE-READ PAIRS
1784 //
1785 // If we don't put unordered write-read pairs into some order at Verilation
1786 // time, we risk a runtime race.
1787 //
1788 // How do such unordered writer/reader pairs happen? Here's a partial list
1789 // of scenarios:
1790 //
1791 // Case 1: Circular logic
1792 //
1793 // If the design has circular logic, V3Order has by now generated some
1794 // dependency cycles, and also cut some of the edges to make it
1795 // acyclic.
1796 //
1797 // For serial mode, that was fine. We can break logic circles at an
1798 // arbitrary point. At runtime, we'll repeat the _eval() until no
1799 // changes are detected, which papers over the discarded dependency.
1800 //
1801 // For parallel mode, this situation can lead to unordered reads and
1802 // writes of the same variable, causing a data race. For example if the
1803 // original code is this:
1804 //
1805 // assign b = b | a << 2;
1806 // assign out = b;
1807 //
1808 // ... there's originally a dependency edge which records that 'b'
1809 // depends on the first assign. V3Order may cut this edge, making the
1810 // statements unordered. In serial mode that's fine, they can run in
1811 // either order. In parallel mode it's a reader/writer race.
1812 //
1813 // Case 2: Race Condition in Verilog Sources
1814 //
1815 // If the input has races, eg. blocking assignments in always blocks
1816 // that share variables, the graph at this point will contain unordered
1817 // writes and reads (or unordered write-write pairs) reflecting that.
1818 //
1819 // Case 3: Interesting V3Order Behavior
1820 //
1821 // There's code in V3Order that explicitly avoids making a dependency
1822 // edge from a clock-gater signal to the logic node that produces the
1823 // clock signal. This leads to unordered reader/writer pairs in
1824 // parallel mode.
1825 //
1826
1827 // TYPES
1828 // Sort LogicMTask objects into deterministic order by calling id()
1829 // which is a unique and stable serial number.
1830 struct MTaskIdLessThan final {
1831 bool operator()(const LogicMTask* lhsp, const LogicMTask* rhsp) const {
1832 ✗ return lhsp->id() < rhsp->id();

1834 };
